# SOC Blue Team Lab
## Project 3 – Multi-Stage Attack Detection
### Phase 1–8: Reconnaissance Stage

---

# Overview

The reconnaissance phase represents the first stage of the cyber attack lifecycle. During this stage, attackers attempt to gather information about a target system or network before attempting exploitation.

In this lab environment, reconnaissance activities were simulated using a Kali Linux attacker machine against a Windows target machine. Network traffic generated during reconnaissance was captured and analyzed using Wireshark to simulate how a Security Operations Center (SOC) analyst detects scanning behavior.

MITRE ATT&CK Mapping:

TA0043 — Reconnaissance  
T1046 — Network Service Discovery  
T1016 — System Network Discovery

---

# Lab Environment

| Machine | Role | Example IP |
|------|------|------|
| Kali Linux | Attacker | 192.168.56.106 |
| Windows 10 | Target | 192.168.56.102 |
| Ubuntu / Splunk | Monitoring | 192.168.56.101 |

Network Type:

VirtualBox Host-Only Network

---

# Phase 1 – Lab Preparation

The lab environment was prepared using three virtual machines.

Steps performed:

• Installed Kali Linux attacker machine  
• Installed Windows 10 target machine  
• Installed Ubuntu server for monitoring tools  
• Configured VirtualBox Host-Only network  
• Verified network connectivity between machines

Purpose:

Create an isolated environment for safe attack simulation and defensive monitoring.

---

# Phase 2 – Connectivity Verification

Connectivity between machines was validated before beginning reconnaissance.

Example test:
ping 192.168.56.102

Result:

Successful ICMP replies confirmed that the Kali attacker machine could communicate with the Windows target.

Security Insight:

Before launching reconnaissance, attackers ensure the target system is reachable.

---

# Phase 3 – Host Discovery

Attackers first identify which systems exist on a network.

Command used:
nmap -sn 192.168.56.0/24

Explanation:

• `nmap` – network scanning tool  
• `-sn` – ping scan (host discovery only)  
• `192.168.56.0/24` – scan entire network range

Result:

Active hosts discovered within the lab network including the Kali attacker machine and Windows target machine.

Security Insight:

Host discovery allows attackers to map available targets before conducting deeper scans.

---

# Phase 4 – Port Scanning

After identifying active hosts, attackers scan open ports.

Command used:
nmap -sS 192.168.56.102

Explanation:

• `-sS` – SYN scan (half-open scan)

Purpose:

Identify open ports on the Windows machine.

Observation:

Multiple ports were probed to determine which services were exposed.

Security Insight:

Port scanning is a core reconnaissance technique used to identify attack surfaces.

---

# Phase 5 – Service Discovery

Once open ports are identified, attackers determine which services are running.

Command used:
nmap -sV 192.168.56.102

Explanation:

• `-sV` – service version detection

Purpose:

Identify software services running behind open ports.

Security Insight:

Service version information helps attackers identify known vulnerabilities.

---

# Phase 6 – Stealth Scanning

Attackers sometimes attempt stealth scanning techniques to evade detection.

Example command:
nmap -sF 192.168.56.102

Explanation:

• `-sF` – FIN scan

Purpose:

Attempt to probe ports without using standard SYN packets.

Security Insight:

Stealth scanning attempts to bypass simple intrusion detection rules.

---

# Phase 7 – Traffic Capture and Detection

Network traffic generated during scanning was captured using Wireshark.

Wireshark filter used:
tcp.flags.syn == 1

Purpose:

Identify TCP SYN packets generated during scanning activity.

Observation:

Multiple SYN packets originating from the Kali attacker machine were detected targeting numerous ports on the Windows host.

Security Insight:

Burst SYN traffic targeting many ports is a common indicator of port scanning activity.

---

# Phase 8 – Scan Pattern Visualization

Traffic visualization was performed using Wireshark I/O Graphs.

Filter used:

Purpose:

Identify TCP SYN packets generated during scanning activity.

Observation:

Multiple SYN packets originating from the Kali attacker machine were detected targeting numerous ports on the Windows host.

Security Insight:

Burst SYN traffic targeting many ports is a common indicator of port scanning activity.

---

# Phase 8 – Scan Pattern Visualization

Traffic visualization was performed using Wireshark I/O Graphs.

Filter used:
tcp.flags.syn == 1

Observation:

A spike in SYN packet activity was observed during the scanning operation.

Interpretation:

The spike represents automated scanning activity generated by the Nmap tool.

Security Insight:

SOC analysts frequently use traffic visualization tools to quickly identify abnormal network behaviors such as reconnaissance scanning.

---

# Attacker Behavior Summary

Reconnaissance activities performed in this lab included:

• Network host discovery  
• Port scanning  
• Service enumeration  
• Stealth scanning attempts  

These activities represent typical attacker behavior before attempting system exploitation.

---

# Defender Detection Summary

The reconnaissance activity was successfully detected using defensive monitoring techniques:

• Packet capture using Wireshark  
• SYN packet filtering  
• Traffic spike visualization  
• Source host identification  

This demonstrates how SOC analysts can detect early attack stages through network traffic analysis.

---

# Conclusion

The reconnaissance stage provides attackers with critical intelligence about target systems and network structure.

In this lab, reconnaissance techniques were successfully simulated and analyzed from a defensive perspective. Packet capture and traffic analysis techniques allowed the identification of scanning behavior and attacker activity.

Understanding reconnaissance detection enables SOC analysts to identify potential threats early in the attack lifecycle and take preventative action before exploitation occurs.

